snippet.textDisplay: The spots are caused by gas not being able to vent out of the paint.  As the water spots stay on the surface of the clear coat, the base coat is still gassing out.  Without an escape path, it just stays under the clear.  The clear gasses out also.  This is all a part of the "curing" process.

snippet.textDisplay:
Could it be what is known as solvent pop? If its disappearing, seems to indicate that, instead of some other type of hard water damage. Hard water damage shouldn't ever come from rain water, only from tap or well water. Minerals don't evaporate.

Solvent pop can happen when you put on things like clear too thick per coat and don't allow enough dry time between coats. The solvents get trapped and create micro bubbles. Do you have micro bubbles in the paint?
snippet.textOriginal:
Could it be what is known as solvent pop?  If its disappearing, seems to indicate that, instead of some other type of hard water damage.  Hard water damage shouldn't ever come from rain water, only from tap or well water.  Minerals don't evaporate.

Solvent pop can happen when you put on things like clear too thick per coat and don't allow enough dry time between coats.  The solvents get trapped and create micro bubbles.  Do you have micro bubbles in the paint?
